</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Synthetic mammography (SM) consists of two-dimensional images reconstructed from digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) data. Unlike standard full-field digital mammography (FFDM), SM does not require additional radiation exposure. SM is being introduced in breast imaging centers because early clinical data demonstrate that synthetic images are comparable to FFDM in cancer detection, positive predictive values, and recall rates. SM has completely replaced FFDM in some practices. Thus, an understanding of SM and its strengths and weaknesses compared with those of FFDM is essential. The artifacts of SM include blurring subcutaneous tissue, loss of resolution in the axilla on mediolateral oblique views, pseudocalcifications, and decreased resolution near foreign bodies (eg, biopsy markers). SM’s strengths include a reduced radiation dose, shorter acquisition time compared with a combined FFDM/DBT screening examination (with potentially less motion artifact), and increased conspicuity of calcifications, spiculated margins, and architectural distortion. The weaknesses of SM include the potential for false positives due to pseudocalcifications and the difficulty in assessing for motion artifact. This article reviews SM and its role in screening and presents clinical cases to highlight SM’s strengths, weaknesses, and artifacts.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017170032">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017170032">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig1a.jpeg" height="2263" width="2414" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show grouped calcifications (□) in the lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show grouped amorphous calcifications (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show better visualization of the calcifications (arrow). Results of a stereotactic core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm ductal carcinoma in situ, solid and cribriform types (intermediate nuclear grade).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig1b.jpeg" height="2250" width="2414" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show grouped calcifications (□) in the lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show grouped amorphous calcifications (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show better visualization of the calcifications (arrow). Results of a stereotactic core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm ductal carcinoma in situ, solid and cribriform types (intermediate nuclear grade).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig1c.jpeg" height="1034" width="1137" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show grouped calcifications (□) in the lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show grouped amorphous calcifications (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show better visualization of the calcifications (arrow). Results of a stereotactic core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm ductal carcinoma in situ, solid and cribriform types (intermediate nuclear grade).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig1d.jpeg" height="1034" width="1136" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show grouped calcifications (□) in the lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show grouped amorphous calcifications (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show better visualization of the calcifications (arrow). Results of a stereotactic core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm ductal carcinoma in situ, solid and cribriform types (intermediate nuclear grade).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig1e.jpeg" height="1100" width="1137" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show grouped calcifications (□) in the lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show grouped amorphous calcifications (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show better visualization of the calcifications (arrow). Results of a stereotactic core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm ductal carcinoma in situ, solid and cribriform types (intermediate nuclear grade).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig1f.jpeg" height="1100" width="1136" aria-labelledby="fig1f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1f</span>. Calcifications in a 51-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Left <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show grouped calcifications (□) in the lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show grouped amorphous calcifications (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show better visualization of the calcifications (arrow). Results of a stereotactic core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm ductal carcinoma in situ, solid and cribriform types (intermediate nuclear grade).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig1f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2a.jpeg" height="1605" width="2350" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2b.jpeg" height="1502" width="2350" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2c.jpeg" height="960" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2d.jpeg" height="1014" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2e.jpeg" height="1006" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig2e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2e</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2f.jpeg" height="1098" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig2f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2f</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig2g.jpeg" height="1098" width="1496" aria-labelledby="fig2g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2g</span>. Mass in a 49-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right lower inner breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show a lesion (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show improved visualization of the spiculated margins of the lesion (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse ultrasonographic (US) image shows an irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins, which correlates with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive and human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig2g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig3a.jpeg" height="1800" width="2350" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Architectural distortion in a 50-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO (left) and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> (right) <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images <b>(b)</b> show a lesion (○) in the right upper outer breast. <b>(c, d)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images show possible architectural distortion (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Digitally magnified <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(f)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show the architectural distortion with better clarity (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Transverse US image shows a small irregular hypoechoic solid mass correlating with the mammographic finding. Results of US-guided core needle biopsy (not shown) helped confirm invasive ductal carcinoma, which was grade 1, estrogen receptor and progesterone receptor positive, and HER2/neu negative.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig3b.jpeg" height="1984" width="2350" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="