<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show a bright band (arrows) in the subcutaneous tissue just beneath the skin. <b>(c, d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images do not show the bright band (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig4b.jpeg" height="2252" width="1120" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Subcutaneous tissue blurring (bright-band artifact). <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show a bright band (arrows) in the subcutaneous tissue just beneath the skin. <b>(c, d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images do not show the bright band (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig4c.jpeg" height="2252" width="1062" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Subcutaneous tissue blurring (bright-band artifact). <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show a bright band (arrows) in the subcutaneous tissue just beneath the skin. <b>(c, d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images do not show the bright band (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig4d.jpeg" height="2184" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Subcutaneous tissue blurring (bright-band artifact). <b>(a, b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> images show a bright band (arrows) in the subcutaneous tissue just beneath the skin. <b>(c, d)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images do not show the bright band (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig5a.jpeg" height="2175" width="1272" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Loss of skin resolution (burned-skin artifact). <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image shows loss of visualization of the skin (solid arrows). Note the bright line (dashed arrow) from the abrupt tissue-air interface. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image shows clear visualization of the skin (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig5b.jpeg" height="2175" width="1382" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Loss of skin resolution (burned-skin artifact). <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image shows loss of visualization of the skin (solid arrows). Note the bright line (dashed arrow) from the abrupt tissue-air interface. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image shows clear visualization of the skin (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig6a.jpeg" height="2284" width="1225" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Decreased axillary contrast resolution artifact. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows decreased resolution in the axilla (▭) compared with that of the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b>. This is secondary to the dominance of the homogeneous pectoralis muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig6b.jpeg" height="2284" width="1220" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Decreased axillary contrast resolution artifact. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows decreased resolution in the axilla (▭) compared with that of the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b>. This is secondary to the dominance of the homogeneous pectoralis muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig7a.jpeg" height="2269" width="1279" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Decreased axillary resolution at <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> due to high density in the axilla at FDDM. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows decreased resolution (▭) in the axilla due to the high density of the patient’s arm (arrow) seen on the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b>. The density artifact is amplified by the tomosynthesis arc.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig7b.jpeg" height="2269" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Decreased axillary resolution at <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> due to high density in the axilla at FDDM. <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows decreased resolution (▭) in the axilla due to the high density of the patient’s arm (arrow) seen on the <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b>. The density artifact is amplified by the tomosynthesis arc.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig8a.jpeg" height="2304" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) show possible calcification (arrow) in the outer breast. <b>(b)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) do not show the possible calcification (arrow). The pseudocalcification was not seen on <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> or <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images, and it was determined to be artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig8b.jpeg" height="2234" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) show possible calcification (arrow) in the outer breast. <b>(b)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) do not show the possible calcification (arrow). The pseudocalcification was not seen on <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> or <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> images, and it was determined to be artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig9a.jpeg" height="2036" width="1031" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a, b)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows possible calcifications (□) in the outer breast, and a digitally magnified <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b> more clearly shows the calcifications. <b>(c, d)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images of the questioned lesion (□) do not show the calcifications. <b>(e, f)</b> Right spot magnification <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(f)</b> mammograms of the questioned lesion show no calcifications, confirming that the finding is artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig9b.jpeg" height="1118" width="1355" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a, b)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows possible calcifications (□) in the outer breast, and a digitally magnified <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b> more clearly shows the calcifications. <b>(c, d)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images of the questioned lesion (□) do not show the calcifications. <b>(e, f)</b> Right spot magnification <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(f)</b> mammograms of the questioned lesion show no calcifications, confirming that the finding is artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig9c.jpeg" height="2037" width="1255" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a, b)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows possible calcifications (□) in the outer breast, and a digitally magnified <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b> more clearly shows the calcifications. <b>(c, d)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images of the questioned lesion (□) do not show the calcifications. <b>(e, f)</b> Right spot magnification <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(f)</b> mammograms of the questioned lesion show no calcifications, confirming that the finding is artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig9d.jpeg" height="1118" width="1237" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a, b)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows possible calcifications (□) in the outer breast, and a digitally magnified <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b> more clearly shows the calcifications. <b>(c, d)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images of the questioned lesion (□) do not show the calcifications. <b>(e, f)</b> Right spot magnification <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(f)</b> mammograms of the questioned lesion show no calcifications, confirming that the finding is artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig9e.jpeg" height="2036" width="1414" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a, b)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows possible calcifications (□) in the outer breast, and a digitally magnified <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b> more clearly shows the calcifications. <b>(c, d)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images of the questioned lesion (□) do not show the calcifications. <b>(e, f)</b> Right spot magnification <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(f)</b> mammograms of the questioned lesion show no calcifications, confirming that the finding is artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig9f.jpeg" height="1118" width="1114" aria-labelledby="fig9f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9f</span>. Pseudocalcification. <b>(a, b)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(a)</b> shows possible calcifications (□) in the outer breast, and a digitally magnified <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image <b>(b)</b> more clearly shows the calcifications. <b>(c, d)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(c)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> images of the questioned lesion (□) do not show the calcifications. <b>(e, f)</b> Right spot magnification <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> <b>(e)</b> and digitally magnified <b>(f)</b> mammograms of the questioned lesion show no calcifications, confirming that the finding is artifactual.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig9f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig10a.jpeg" height="1919" width="2992" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Artifact from a metallic foreign body. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) show an artifact from a biopsy clip (arrow) that obscures the mass it is within. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) show the mass and the biopsy clip (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig10b.jpeg" height="1938" width="2992" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Artifact from a metallic foreign body. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) show an artifact from a biopsy clip (arrow) that obscures the mass it is within. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image and digitally magnified view (▭) show the mass and the biopsy clip (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170032&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170032/asset/images/large/rg.2017170032.fig11a.jpeg" height="2397" width="1095" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Difficulty in assessing for motion artifact. <b>(a)</b> Single-section <abbr title="digital breast tomosynthesis">DBT</abbr> image shows blurring. The patient sneezed during image acquisition, and motion artifact was evident in cine mode. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="synthetic mammography">SM</abbr> image does not show the motion artifact. <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> <abbr title="full-field digital mammography">FFDM</abbr> image does not demonstrate motion artifact, as this is a separate acquisition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-fi